To transform the first and third lines to form an "X" when the button is clicked, you've got most of the necessary CSS defined. However, let's correct the syntax for standard CSS and make sure the transforms are correctly positioned to form a crossing shape.

Also, the transform-origin for both the `.first` and `.third` lines should match to ensure they rotate around the same point. The units of transform on both should also be consistent to create a symmetrical 'X'.

Assuming you don't use SCSS (Sass), here's the corrected CSS:

```css
.hamburger-line {
  width: 100%;
  background: #f13024;
  height: 2px;
  display: block;
  border-radius: 6px;
  transition: transform 0.4s cubic-bezier(0.54, -0.81, 0.57, 0.57);
  position: relative;
}

/* Width is set to 100% for first and third lines, this can be adjusted if necessary */
.hamburger-line.first,
.hamburger-line.third {
  width: 100%;
}

/* Specify transform-origin for the rotation point */
.hamburger-line.first,
.hamburger-line.third {
  transform-origin: center;
}

/* Translate values need to be adjusted to fit the size of your button */
.hamburger-line.first.toggled {
  transform: translateY(9px) rotate(45deg);
}

.hamburger-line.second.toggled {
  opacity: 0;
}

.hamburger-line.third.toggled {
  transform: translateY(-9px) rotate(-45deg);
}
```

Make sure that when you're applying the toggled class, you apply it correctly as per the state in your React component. When `isNavVisible` is `true` (meaning the navigation menu is open), the `.toggled` class should be applied to both `.first` and `.third` lines to transform them into an "X".

Adjust the translateY values if necessary, depending on the size of your button and the desired visual effect.

Here's the updated JSX for the button:

```jsx
<button
  className="hamburger-btn" // Add your styles or classes here
  onClick={toggleNav} // Attach the toggle function
  aria-label="Toggle navigation"
>
  <div className="icon-wrapper">
    <label className="hamburger">
      <span className={`hamburger-line first ${isNavVisible ? 'toggled' : ''}`}></span>
      <span className={`hamburger-line second ${isNavVisible ? 'toggled' : ''}`}></span>
      <span className={`hamburger-line third ${isNavVisible ? 'toggled' : ''}`}></span>
    </label>
  </div>
</button>
```

Now, when the `.hamburger-btn` is clicked, the `.toggled` class should be applied to both `.first` and `.third` lines causing them to rotate around their center and form an "X" shape. The middle line fades away since its opacity is set to 0.

